    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-06-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-06-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="613"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d613">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Marshall Mission Files, Lot 54–D270</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by General <persName type="from">Chou
                            En-lai</persName> to General <persName type="to">Marshall</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="7" xml:id="d613fn7">Reported by General Marshall to Mr. Robertson at
                        Peiping in Telegram No. 1025, June 30, not printed.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">MM 064</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-06-29">June 29,
                            1946</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>It is reliably learned that the Government will launch an attack on Communist
                    Jehol area in case the peace negotiation suffers a deadlock. Your attention is
                    therefore called to the following plan contemplated by the Government:</p>
                <p>The main force of the 71st and the 13th armies, which are now stationed in Jehol
                    and western Liaoning, will sally out from Pingchuan (118°36′; 41°1′) city to
                    attack the city of Chengteh (117°51′; 40°58′), and another part of the force
                    will advance westward from the area to the west of the cities of Suichung
                    (120°11′; 40°20′) and Chinsi (120°28′; 40°56′), while the 92nd army, now
                    stationed at Miyun city (116°50′; 40°25′) to the North of Peiping, will assault
                    Kupeikou (117°10′; 40°45′) and Hsifengkou (118°17′; 40°28′) in a concerted
                    military action.</p>
                <closer>[Signature in Chinese]<lb/>(<signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Chou En-lai</hi>
                    </signed>)</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
